<PubmedArticle><MedlineCitation Status="MEDLINE" Owner="NLM" IndexingMethod="Automated"><PMID Version="1">41759849</PMID><DateCompleted><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>15</Day></DateCompleted><DateRevised><Year>2026</Year><Month>03</Month><Day>15</Day></DateRevised><Article PubModel="Print-Electronic"><Journal><ISSN IssnType="Electronic">1879-0003</ISSN><JournalIssue CitedMedium="Internet"><Volume>352</Volume><PubDate><Year>2026</Year><Month>Mar</Month></PubDate></JournalIssue><Title>International journal of biological macromolecules</Title><ISOAbbreviation>Int J Biol Macromol</ISOAbbreviation></Journal><ArticleTitle>Porous-hydrophilic synergy in wearable nylon-6/cellulose/KOH humidity sensors for high-sensitivity health monitoring.</ArticleTitle><Pagination><StartPage>151110</StartPage><MedlinePgn>151110</MedlinePgn></Pagination><ELocationID EIdType="doi" ValidYN="Y">10.1016/j.ijbiomac.2026.151110</ELocationID><ELocationID EIdType="pii" ValidYN="Y">S0141-8130(26)01036-6</ELocationID><Abstract><AbstractText>In this work, the development and characterization of a high-performance polymer-based humidity sensor composed of a nylon6 (PA6), cellulose acetate (CA) composite and KOH. The introduction of K<sup>+</sup> ions establish an effective ion-conduction pathway, which-combined with the porous structure formed via phase transition and the abundant hydrophilic groups in the PA6/CA matrix-creates a synergistic enhancement in humidity sensitivity. The PA6/CA/KOH sensor exhibits exceptional humidity response performance, delivering a maximum response value of 3931% at 98% relative humidity (RH) across a broad detection range of 33-98% RH. It demonstrates response and recovery times of 186&#xa0;s and 146&#xa0;s, respectively, along with excellent cyclic stability. Additionally, the sensor possesses robust mechanical properties, including a maximum elongation stress of 1412.60&#xa0;kPa and an elongation modulus of 1681.66&#xa0;kPa, ensuring flexibility and durability. As a proof-of-concept, the sensor has been successfully applied in human respiration monitoring and non-contact fingertip humidity detection, underscoring its potential for integration into sports health monitoring, wearable devices, and portable healthcare systems.</AbstractText><CopyrightInformation>Copyright &#xa9; 2026. Published by Elsevier B.V.</CopyrightInformation></Abstract><AuthorList CompleteYN="Y"><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Yi</LastName><ForeName>Yanbin</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Bioresource Chemical and Materials Engineering, Shaanxi University of Science &amp; Technology, Xi'an, 710021, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Jiang</LastName><ForeName>Xue</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Bioresource Chemical and Materials Engineering, Shaanxi University of Science &amp; Technology, Xi'an, 710021, China. Electronic address: jiangx@sust.edu.cn.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Tian</LastName><ForeName>Xiuzhi</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Bioresource Chemical and Materials Engineering, Shaanxi University of Science &amp; Technology, Xi'an, 710021, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Li</LastName><ForeName>Yuhang</ForeName><Initials>Y</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Bioresource Chemical and Materials Engineering, Shaanxi University of Science &amp; Technology, Xi'an, 710021, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Wang</LastName><ForeName>Xin</ForeName><Initials>X</Initials><AffiliationInfo><Affiliation>College of Bioresource Chemical and Materials Engineering, Shaanxi University of Science &amp; Technology, Xi'an, 710021, China.</Affiliation></AffiliationInfo></Author><Author ValidYN="Y"><LastName>Xiang</LastName><ForeName>Zhong</ForeName><Initials>Z</Init